<doc id="146806" wikidata="Q740970" url="?curid=146806" title="Recurrence relation">
<text>In mathematics, a recurrence relation is an equation according to which the formula_1th term of a sequence of numbers is equal to some combination of the previous terms. Often, only formula_2 previous terms of the sequence appear in the equation, for a parameter formula_2 that is independent of formula_1; this number formula_2 is called the &quot;order&quot; of the relation. If the values of the first formula_2 numbers in the sequence have been given, the rest of the sequence can be calculated by repeatedly applying the equation.

In &quot;linear recurrences&quot;, the th term is equated to a linear function of the formula_2 previous terms. A famous example is the recurrence for the Fibonacci numbers,
formula_8
where the order formula_2 is two and the linear function merely adds the two previous terms. This example is a linear recurrence with constant coefficients, because the coefficients of the linear function (1 and 1) are constants that do not depend on formula_10 For these recurrences, one can express the general term of the sequence as a closed-form expression of formula_1. As well, linear recurrences with polynomial coefficients depending on formula_1 are also important, because many common elementary functions and special functions have a Taylor series whose coefficients satisfy such a recurrence relation (see holonomic function).

Solving a recurrence relation means obtaining a closed-form solution: a non-recursive function of formula_1.

The concept of a recurrence relation can be extended to multidimensional arrays, that is, indexed families that are indexed by tuples of natural numbers.

==Definition==
A &quot;recurrence relation&quot; is an equation that expresses each element of a sequence as a function of the preceding ones. More precisely, in the case where only the immediately preceding element is involved, a recurrence relation has the form
:formula_14
where 
:formula_15
is a function, where is a set to which the elements of a sequence must belong. For any formula_16, this defines a unique sequence with formula_17 as its first element, called the &quot;initial value&quot;.

It is easy to modify the definition for getting sequences starting from the term of index 1 or higher.

This defines recurrence relation of &quot;first order&quot;. A recurrence relation of &quot;order&quot; has the form 
:formula_18

where formula_19 is a function that involves consecutive elements of the sequence.
In this case, initial values are needed for defining a sequence.

